{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958042501/0298.xml":{"full_text":"Depression Is Now at Hand,\nMeany Warns Congress\n(Oonttned from Page One)\nThis stark fact America must face\nwith honesty and determination.\nAmerica has shown Its greatness\u2014in\nwar and peace\u2014only when it has been\nwilling to face the truth\u2014and to take\nWhatever action may be necessary.\nConfidence in America\u2019s basic eco\nnomlc strength can only be maintain\ned by the knowledge that corrective\nsteps are being taken.\nOn March 11, I publicly warned\nthat unices the March unemployment\nfigures showed a seasonal drop of at\nleast 200,009 Jobs, we would be in\nserious trouble. Instead of this drop,\nhowever, there has been an actual in\ncrease in March unemployment.\nToday more than 5,200,000 Amer\nicans are jobless. Today more than\n3% million Americans are working\nfar leas than a full work week, adding\nthe economic equivalent of 1.3 mil\nlion to the unemployment ifgure. As\na practical matter then, nearly\nof our labor force is jobless.\nClose ito 45,000 workers are ex\nhausting their unemployment com\npensation benefits every week.\nIt is on behalf of these people\u2014\nthese millions of American Workers\nthat 1 am writing you today. Many of\nthem are members of our unions. All\nof them are members of that great\nhuman family that is America. Their\nsuffering cannot be measured statls\ntlcally. There are no statistics which\nv can measure the fears of a worker and\nhis family at a time like this.\nUnless America acts now to stop\nthis suffering, inevitably additional\nmillions will soon join the ranks of\nthe unemployed. Every important in\ndicator continues to point downward.\nThere isn\u2019t a single ray of sunshine\non the economic scene.\nThe Congress of the United States\nthus faces a grave challenge. The\ncountry is looking to you for the swift,\nmeaningful action which the Congress\nhas demonstrated in past crises.\nI am aware of the anti-recession\nmeasures adopted to date by the\nCongress and the measures which the\nAdministration is supporting. The\neconomists- of the AFLr-CIO, after\ncareful and thorough study, have con\ncluded that these- measures, might\npump up to a total of a billion dol\nlars into the economy this year. But\nat a time when the United States is\nMitchell Finds Many Child\nLabor Law Violations^\nSecretary of Labor James P. Mit\nchell reported that during fiscal 1957\nLabor Department Investigators found\nover 11,000 minors employed In viola\ntion of child labor pro visions of the\nPair Labor Standards Act. These in\ncluded 5,867 yrorldng Illegally in nan\nagricultural establishments and 6,477\non farms.\nOf the 5,477 farm-employed chil\ndren, 20 per cent, or 1,097, ranged\nin age from 4 to 9 years and 52 per\ncent, or 2,848, were 10 to 18 yearn\nold.\nSecretary Mitchell cited these\nfindings In announcing his annual\nreport to the Congress for the year\nended June 30, 1957.\nIn Issuing the report, the Labor\nSecretary deplored what he called\n\u2018'this exploitation of children.\"\n\u2018\u2018It Is the purpose of child labor\nlaws to assure the youth of the Na\ntlon the chance of an education and\nhealthful and safe employment If they\nmust work in their teens,\u201d he said.\n\"Only about 5 per cent of all jobs\nl available on an age basis to young\npeople between 16 and 18 are restrict\ned, and these are in occupations\nwhich experience and study have\nshown to be very hazardous.\n\"In view of the evidence in this\nreport, It is clear that child labor\ntaws are still very much needed, and\nI intend to see to it that those for\nwhich I am responsible are strictly\nenforced,\u201d\nAlmost 4,000 of the Illegally em\nployed youngsters were working In\nJobs which had been declared hazard\npus by the Secretary of Labor. The\nPair labor Standards Act sets an\n18-year minimum age for hazardous\noccupations, a 16-year wi\u00bbi\u00abinm for\ngeneral employment, and a 14-year\nminimum for certain after-ochool\nChildren under 14 were found work\nlag In such hazardous Jobs es skidding\nlogs, cutting, loading, and hauling\npulpwood, driving a tractor to haul\nlogs to the sawmill, operating a\nfreight elevator at a wholesale beer\n?concern, operating a scrap-paper bal\ntag machine, and acting as helpers on\nmilk and safe drink delivery trucks.\nOthers in baraazdoue Jobs included\n14- and 15-year-olds employed In mln\nlag of coal and manganese ore, ope\nrating a poweevdrtven platen press\nand a gumottns papsrcutter, and\nA1 botUng xomt tad butchering on tht\nisiBtng fiodr of pimt.\nFor some of these youngsters, Owe\n-U/-\nlosing 25 billion dollars a year In na\ntional production, this puny economic\nblood transfusion cannot possibly re\nstore the economy to good health,\nr Clearly Congress must take bidder\naction.\nfirst, priority most be given to re\nlieving the plight of the unemployed\nthemselves. This can be done by the\nadoption of an unemployment com\npensation bill which win require larg\ner benefits sad longer dnratton. The\nMcCarthy-Kennedy bffl deserves your\nfull support. Substantial Increases in\nunemployment compensation pay\nments will not only help the reci\npients but will increase general pur\nchasing power which will in turn\nhelp the entire economy.\nIn order to relieve the plight of the\neconomy itself, we renew our recom\nmendation for a substantial tax cut\nwhich will affect primarily the lower\nand middle income groups. A 8 to 8\nbillion dollar tax reduction in both\npersonal income and excise taxes\ncould be decisive in the present situa\ntion.\nThe AFL-CIO has called for other\nanti-recession measures These in\nclude a real public works program,\nschool construction, a much bigger\nhousing program, an increase end\nextension of the federal minimum\nwage, improvements in the social se\ncurity program, and depressed areas\nlegislation.\nClearly, now Is the time for Amer\nica to act before confidence in the\nbedrock soundness of our economy be\ncomes undermined. To wait further\nweeks or months will only add to the\nsuffering of millions and the need\nfor more drastic and costly measures\nlater.\n'Only last week a spokesman for\nthe Soviet Union predicted .that Amer\nica would not be able to get out of its\neconomic difficulties.\nWe' can prove these Communist\nspokesmen wrong. We can end the\neconomic recession. We can move on\nto further economic growth. But we\nmust be willing to face the facts.\nAmerica has shown in the past that\nfree enterprise can meet any chal\nlenge, from any source. We believe It\ncan again\u2014if we get on with the Job\nat once.\nAll America Is looking to the Con\ngress for action to end this recession.\njobs ended with fatal or permanently\ndisabling injuries.\nAmong the fatalities reported:\nA freight elevator took the life of\na 18-year-old midwee tern boy when\nhis head struck the basement celling\nas he leaned out of the rising elevator.\nA 16-year-old high school student\nIn a Pacific Coast State was killed\nwhen a forklift he was operating sud\ndenly ran out of control, tipped over,\nand pinned him under It.\nIn the Southeast, a 15-year-old\ntruckdrlver waa fatally injured In n\ngravel pit when a bank caved in.\nAnother southeastern bey, 16 years\nof age, who had been working as an\noffbearer In a sawmill for 6 days, suf\nfered fatal Injuries when a belt broke\nand part of the lacing hit him over\nthe heart.\nAs a result of investigations by the\nDepartment\u2019s Wage and Hour and\nPublic Contracts Divisions, 3,102 min\nors under 18 were removed from un\nsuitable employment as Cruckdrivers\nor helpers, 812 from employment as\noperators of elevators or other hoist\ning apparatus, and 790 from hazard\nous work in logging and s&wmllling.\nOthers removed included 134 from\nI power-driven metal forming and\nshearing-machine operations and 83\nfrom illegal occupations in slaughter\ning, meatpacking, and rendering\nplants.The investigators found 2,504\nboys and girls under 16 who ware\nemployed in violation of the basic 16\nyear minimum age requirement.\nIronically, many of the illegally em\nployed children werev underpaid.\n\u201cFirms that unlawfully employ chil\ndren often compound Chair chUd.labor\nviolations by falling to pay young\nsters the lawful minimum wage,'\u2019 the\nSecretary points out in his report A\nfruit drying yard in the West em\nploying almost 300 children ranging\nin age from 6 to 16, was found Co owe\n522,258 for minimum wage viola\ntions. Many of the children had work\ned a day or more without any pay,\nwhile others averaged as,little as 10\ncents an hour.\nProtestant Churches of\nOhio Fight Against\n\u2018Right-to-Work*\nVV-V\nT: f\n-V# U\nCatholic Bishops of Ohio. In their\nstead \u00ab(ilait \u201cright-to-work\u201d laws,\ntbs Bishops said they would oppose a\nstate law requiring onion\nship Just as they are opposing a state\nlaw forbidding a onion shop.\nThere is no. state law which re\nquires the union shop. The issue is\ndetermined hi the free collective bar\ngaining process and by a vote of the\nworkers. However, the Ohio Cham\nber's proposal would prohibit union\nshop agreements and make the open\nshop compulsory.\nThe \u201cright-to-work\u201d campaign of\nthe Ohio Chamber of Commerce was\nalso,., condemned recently by Rabbi\nAbba H. Silver of Cleveland. Rabbi\nSilver called the \"right-to-work\u201d pro\nposal a \"misleading device\u201d being\nused by \u201cpowerful business organiza\ntions\u201d to destroy unions.\nThe complete resolution adopted\nat the Protestant Church session fol\nlows:\n\u201cThe current proposal to place on\nthe ballot la Ohio a constitutional\nchange being called by its proponents\na \u201cright-to-work\u201d or \"freedom of\nchoice\u201d amendment is a matter for\nthe concern not alone of the workers\nand employers directly affected, but\nof all citizens of the state.\nN.L.R.B. \u2018UNION-BUSTING\u2019\nCHALLENGED IN COURT\n(Continued from Pace One)'\nShefferman\u2019a services. Shefferman\u2019s\nunion-busting activities have been\ncritdzed by the McClellan Committee.\nAccording to RCIA Vice Pres. Sam\nMeyers, the Labor-Management Com\nmittee of Toledo was on the verge of\nreaching an agreement favorable Jo\nthe union when the three stores de\nmanded a single NLRB representation\nelection, counting on the ISO strike\nbreakers in the struck store to win a\nno-unlon majority.\nThe two locals immediately object\ned and demanded single store elections\nso that the mans vote of the strike\nbreakers would not overwhelm the\nwishes of the workers at the other\ntwo stores for ROIA representation.\nAt the same time, officials of the\nlocals refused to. file Taft-Hartley\naffidavits as a technical means of pre\nventing the election. In a 1947 deci\nsion, the NX.RB had ruled 'that a un\nion would not be placed on a ballot\nif It were not in compliance with the\nnon-Oommuniat oath provisions of\nTaft-Hartley.\nHowever,' in ruling on the Toledo\ncase on April 11, the NLRB not only\nOhio SUB\nfrom a test case filed last October\nby the United Steelworkers of Amer\nica and supported by the major steel\ncompanies.\nWhen informed of the Appellate\nCourt decision upholding Judge\nMaiden's ruling, the Ohio CIO Coun\ncil commented:\n\u201cThe Common Pleas Court deci\nsion, now affirmed by a Court of Ap\npeals, Is sufficient Indication that\nSUB payments are perfectly legal\nin Ohio, as they have been declared\nto be in 40 other states.\u201d\nThe Ohio CIO oouncil stated two\nweeks ago that an estimated 90,000\nlaid-off workers already would have\nbeen eligible to receive SUB if the\nState had not followed an antl-SUB\npolicy. The Oouncil said that SUB\npayments to the laif-off workens\nwould be 01,634,018 a week.\nUnion Show\n(Continued from Pago One)\nthey saw twenty yeare ago. They will\nmarvel at the expanded scope of the\nAFL-CIO Union-Industries Shoes the\nbigger and more colorful displays;\nadded free prise drawings; a greater\namy of talent had entertainment and\nn graphic picture of the skills of\nmembers of AFL-CIO ualoas which\nwere not represented prior to the\nmerger of the AFL-CIO.\nAs in all other flelda of endeavor,\nthe. AFL-CIO through its own Union\nLabel and Service Trades Department,\nhas made great and merltoriuoe\nstrides in the field of showmanship\nwith a capital \"S.\"\nThe AFL-CIO Union Label and\nOervice Trades Department locks\nwith confidence toward its third\ndecade in the presentation at tola\ngreat monument to toe millions of\nunion workens rspraasatad by the\nAIL-COO. ...V\n\"The Public Attain Committee of\nthe Ohio ft\u2014<* of Churchea be\nlieves It should be mode dear that\nthe proposal weald not provide work\nfor say unemployed, and that It would\ndeny the freedom of labor onions sad\nemployers to ehoese the form of ualoa\nsecurity known as' the onion shop,\nwhich Is permitted by federal law. It\neoofers not a right to work hot a\nright to share the benefits of orgaa\nIsatloa without sharing its responsi\nbility. A trnthfol descriptive title\nwould be \"csmpulsoiy open ahop,\u201d not\n\"right to work.\"\n\"The Ohio Oooncil of Cfcnrcheo ea\ndorsee the statement of the Kxeco\ntlve Board of the Division of Life aad\nWork of the National Oouncy of\nChorcheo that \u201cunion membership as\na basis of oonttnned employment\noboidd bo neltbor required nor for\nbidden by law: the decision should bo\nleft to agreement by management\nand labor through the process of col\nlective bargaining.\u201d\n\"We urge the citizens of Ohio to\nreject legal proposals which will\nmake either the open or onion shop\ncompulsory. Such proposals are un\ndesirable and incompatible with the\ndevelopment of each management-la\nbor relations as ate in accord with\npublic interest.\u201d;\nupset 'the 1M7/decision- but also de\ncided that a single election must be\nheld.\nThe effect of the ruling Is to extend\nwhat President Eisenhower fans call\ned the \"union-busting\u201d features of the\nTaft-Hartley Act, since the board\u2019s\nposition now permits employers to\nwithdraw from Joint store negotia\ntions while unions are denied this\nright.\nIt also meant that while unions\ncan\u2019t appear on NLRB ballots unless\nthey are in compliance, employers can\nforce a vote on a union even if it is\ndeliberately not in compliance to\n\\void the board\u2019s interference. This\ncan be dohe, as in the present case,\nat a time when the union has been\nforced into a minority position be\ncause of T-H provisions which permit\nstrikebreakers to vote but forbid the\nvote to strikers.\nSol J. Llppman, the union's at\ntorney, charged that the NLftB ac\ntion was \"a naked effort to break a\nstrike.\u201d Meyers said that the union\nwould \"fight the board\u2019s decision with\nevery legal and economic weapon at\nour command.\u201d He added that the\nunion is asking Congress to investi\ngate \"evidence of impropriety\u201d by\nthe NLRB in the case.\nTruman\n((MM'tai ivi\nand dangerous atnoa World War H,\"\nTruman chained dnt the \u201croot of the\ndifficulty*\u2019 is a departure from the\n'iphJIosophjrof maximum amploynunt,\nproduction and purchasing power act\nforth in the Employment Act of\n1946.\"\nTo match our tahor-fSeee growth\nof 1 per cent and oar productivity In\ncrease of S per cent a year, he said,\n\u201cour total wattonal product needa to\nexpand by about tS per cent a year.\u201d\nThe rate of growth averaged above\nU per cent for toe year 1947-58, ha\naaU, but during the yean 1996-67 It\naHpped to 2.8 per cent.\nThere la the cause, he aald, of 'Th\ning unemployment and Idle produc\ntive faculties.\u201d\nThere has been an unnecessary loea\nin five yeans of \u201c8.5 million man\nyean\u201d through joblessness and part\ntime work undre-employment.\nTide \u201ctremendous waste\u201d ot man\npower and productive facilities baa\nmeant \u201ca loea of man than $55 bil\nlion. in wages and salaries, $25 billion\nin farm itaoome, $12 wiiinw in cor\nporate profits, $6 whiwi in unincor\nporated business and professional in\ncome.\u201d\n(hi specific points Truman made\nthe following comments:\nDespite \"claims\" from President\nEisenhower that the 1955 budget will\nshow a slight surplus, \u201cpractically\nevery Informed expert expects a defi\ncit between $4 and $8 billion.\u201d This\nestimate was net challenged by com\nmittee members.\nThe deficit'is \"due in large part\nto the recession\u201d and the recession in\nturn is doe \"to the inability of con\nsumers to buy.\u201d What the consumer\nlacks \"la not confidence but income\nafter taxes.\u201d\nHis own administration had not\nbeen \"entirely successful\u201d In dealing\nwith employment and \"we M an eco\nnomic recessionIn 1949.\u201d But It was\nnot \"no prolonged and deep\u201d as the\ncurrent slump, and \"one thing we\nlearned was that perhaps we should\nhave acted more vigorously than we\ndid.\u201d\nU We should raise defense ok\npenditares, foreign old and welfare\nspending now. Wo should increase do\nmestic investment across five years\nto spend $12 billion for education and\nhealth, $2,5 Milton for natural re\nsources, $U billion for housing and\nurban redevelopment.\nWe would pay the bill from na\ntional output raised from $484 billion\nto $800 billion and have a budget rep\nresenting \"a smaller fraction of total\nproduction.\u201d\ne On tax onto, Congress Should\nbe careful not to pass out benefits to\ninventors and well-to-do people who if\nthey are suffering at all, are suffer\ning only because average families do\nnot have enough purchasing power.\u201d\nMore than 95 per cent of vehicles\ninvolved to fatal accidents on U. 8.\nhighways in 1957 were to apparently\ngood condition.\nGEORGE J.\nMOLL 1C A\nDEMOCRAT for\nSUMMIT COUNTV V\nCOMMISSIONER\nYour Vote WiU B\u00ab Appreciated.\nCOMMUNISTS AGAIN HIT\n,k;\nWORKERS IN POLAND\nmember* to take part in strikes,\nwMA have been legal since OotolMr\n1M6. Another wag a toughening at\nithe government's attitude toward stu\ndents and their demonstrations. A\nthird was a tdamping down on the\nlimited freedom at expression tole\nrated in writers.\nThe Palish potion, must be tied tn\nWith the visit of Premier Khrushchev\nof Russia to Hungary and the speech\nin which he boosted that the Soviet\nArmy is prepared to defend \u2018Asocial\nlot\" countries against \"Counter revo\nlutionaries,\u201d according to Michael\nRoss, director of the ASIr-CIO Depfc\nof Inti. Affairs...\nIt represents a recapture by\nDrahther of control Over those\nsatellites wken M had been slacken\ned,\u201d he said, \u201cand indicates that Go\nmnlha, who was said to have beoome\nhead of the Osmmaniste in Poland\nwith only reluctant support of the\nSoviet, has now made his peace with\nthe Kremlin and feels strong enough\nto defy the forces which helped Mm\nto power.\n\u201cFor the workers, It means that\ntheir unions are nothing bet instru\nments of stale policy, the classic mb\nto which Communists have tradition\nally assigned them.\u201d\nIn his speech Gomnlka hinted\nbroadly at the first frulto of the new\norder when he indicated the party\nsoon will boast the production quotas\ngiven each worker and on which his\nwages areJaased.\nHe told congress .that'new \u2018Asocial\ninstitutions\u201d will cany on the duties\nof the 5,600 councils formed in the\nlast year and a half.\nThe ban On atrlltM is rwtorrtfaw\nof the pre-1956 status. Gtouolka called\nwalkouts\u2018hlgas c\u00ab anarchy appeaiteg\naaU \u201csocial tat* desnocratte frnulni\u2014\nor forme ere clew enemy action.\"*\nThe new anti-strike policy wae.v;\u2018\u201e\nlater slightly modified by Ignacy\nLoga-Sowinski, chairman of the labor Ji\nunions\u2019 central oommittee end a party\nleader. He said workers will still be\nallowed to stop work \u201cfor a few min-\nutee\u201d as a \u201cwarning\" if they are urn- \\'j\u2018i\nable to settle their grievances any\nother way _\nExtended by NLRB\nThe National Labor Relations Board\nhad exten